    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>A theoretical tenet for conserving cultural heritage. The theory maintains that what is old acquires a value of its own due to age, therefore the signs of age, such as patina, should be retained and not corrected or hidden. Based on the philosophy of Viennese art historian Alois Riegl (1858-1905).</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099104/Fisch, National Approaches to the Governance of Historical Heritage (2008)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Theoretisch principe voor de conservatie van cultureel erfgoed. Volgens de theorie krijgt wat oud is alleen al daardoor waarde, en moeten tekenen van ouderdom, zoals patina, worden behouden en niet hersteld of verborgen. Het begrip is gebaseerd op de filosofie van de Weense kunsthistoricus Alois Riegl (1858-1905).
</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
